# How to develop {{PROJECT_NAME}} (human guide)

You don't write code. You direct AI agents through a disciplined loop and judge
the results. This is that loop and your job at each step.

```
discuss -> plan -> review + correct -> execute (worktree) -> review (other CLI) -> land -> verify
  you talk   AI drafts   you approve       AI builds, isolated     cross-check          merge   you UAT
```

One trip through the loop = one phase = one clean commit. Keep loops small.

## 1. Discuss
`gsd-discuss-phase` (first time: `gsd-new-project`). Talk through what you want
next, in plain language. Your job: be clear about the goal and the constraints.

## 2. Plan
`gsd-plan-phase`. The agent writes a step-by-step plan. Your job: wait for it.

## 3. Review + correct the plan
`gsd-review --phase N`
**Don't approve a plan you don't understand — ask until you do.** This is the cheapest
place to catch a mistake; fixing it here costs minutes, fixing it after the build
costs hours.

## 4. Execute in a worktree
`make worktree.new SLUG=<slug>`, then `gsd-execute-phase`. The agent builds in an
isolated copy of the repo (a "git worktree") so your main copy stays clean and
parallel work can't collide. It must keep `make verify` green as it goes.

## 5. Code review by the *other* CLI
Have the other agent review the diff: Claude built it → **Codex reviews**; Codex
built it → **Claude reviews**. A second model catches what the author missed and
won't rubber-stamp its own work. Feed real findings back as fixes; re-run
`make verify`.

## 6. Land the worktree
Once review passes: `make worktree.land SLUG=<slug> MSG="<commit message>"`. It
re-runs `make verify` inside the worktree, lands one clean squash commit, and
deletes the worktree + branch. It refuses if anything is dirty or unverified —
that refusal is the point. Never hand-merge work that skipped review + verify.

## 7. Verify the work
`gsd-verify-work`. Walk through the feature as a real user would and confirm it
does what you asked. Final gate. If it's wrong, go back to discuss/plan — don't
patch blindly.

## Run loops in parallel
The loop is single-threaded by default, but the worktree in step 4 means
independent work doesn't have to wait in line. Look for tasks that don't touch the
same code or depend on each other — a new feature here, a bug fix there, a docs
pass — and push each into its own loop at once. Each runs in its own worktree, so
they can't collide, and you review/land them as they finish.

Your job shifts from "wait for one thing" to **keeping the pipeline full**: while
one phase is executing, you're discussing or reviewing the plan for the next. Be
honest about dependencies though — two loops editing the same module will fight at
land time. When unsure, ask the agent whether two tasks are independent before
starting both.

## Rules of thumb
- Hunt for parallelizable work and keep several independent loops in flight.
- Never approve a plan or a result you don't understand. Ask.
- `make verify` and the other-CLI review are your safety net — don't skip them to
  go faster. Skipping is how slop ships.
- Small loops beat giant ones. One phase at a time.
- Found a good idea or a shortcut you took? File it (`docs/ideas/` /
  `docs/tech_debt/`) so it isn't lost.
